              {
                "type": "output_text",
                "text": "Wikipedia explains Euler's identity (\\(e^{i\\pi} + 1 = 0\\)) as a profound equality connecting several fundamental mathematical constants: \\(e\\) (the base of natural logarithms), \\(\\pi\\) (the ratio of a circle's circumference to its diameter), \\(i\\) (the imaginary unit satisfying \\(i^2 = -1\\)), along with the integers 0 and 1. It is a specific case of Euler's formula (\\(e^{ix} = \\cos(x) + i\\sin(x)\\)) evaluated at \\(x = \\pi\\).\n\nEuler's identity is celebrated for its simplicity and beauty, uniting key mathematical operations—addition, multiplication, and exponentiation—and five critical constants. It is frequently regarded as an iconic example of mathematical aesthetics and is described by mathematicians and physicists as \"mind-blowing\" and \"cosmic\" in beauty.",
